pull_request.title: checker: rewrite comptime_if_cond() to support comptime if cond evaluate
pull_request.body:
<!--

Please title your PR as follows: `module: description` (e.g. `time: fix date format`).
Always start with the thing you are fixing, then describe the fix.
Don't use past tense (e.g. "fixed foo bar").

Explain what your PR does and why.

If you are adding a new function, please document it and add tests:

```
// foo does foo and bar
fn foo() {

// file_test.v
fn test_foo() {
    assert foo() == ...
    ...
}
```

If you are fixing a bug, please add a test that covers it.

Before submitting a PR, please run `v test-all` .
See also `TESTS.md`.

I try to process PRs as soon as possible. They should be handled within 24 hours.

Applying labels to PRs is not needed.

Thanks a lot for your contribution!

-->

This PR:

1. Rewrite `comptime_if_cond()` in `checker`, fully support comptime if conditon evaluate to `true`/`false`.
2. Add comptime iter $for support for enum/method/method params/sumtype variants/attribute.
3. Fix issue #25099, #24938.

for test `vlib/v/gen/c/testdata/comp_if_unknown.vv`

```v
fn main() {
        mut x := 1
        $if glibc {
                x = 2
        } $else {
                x = 3
        }
        println('done')
}
```

I think the output should contain :

```c
#if defined(__GLIBC__)
x = 2;
#else
#endif
```

instead of :

```c
#if defined(__GLIBC__)
x = 2;
#else
x = 3;
#endif
```

release.name: v1.0.0
release.body:
- Type-safe request processing with declare(strict_types=1) and readonly properties
- Modular component architecture with separated concerns and dependency injection
- DI-container friendly - clean classes without complex constructors
- Vendor-independent validation - use any validator implementing our interface
- Field mapping from custom input names and nested structures via dot notation
- Multi-stage processing pipeline (extract  authorize  preprocess  validate  postprocess)
- Built-in authorization framework with simple override mechanisms
- GET query parameter optimization with automatic cleanup and redirect generation
- Custom error messages with detailed validation feedback
- PSR-7 compatible with full HTTP message interface support
- Immutable field definitions using readonly value objects
- Factory methods for component customization without breaking simplicity
release.short_description_html:
• Type-safe request processing with declare(strict_types=1) and readonly properties

pull_request.title: Fix regression in the Path element when used with inheritance
pull_request.body:
After commit ef2e6491cddd619fa00af321d379b77071635b0a we end up processing Paths multiple times, and thus we might end up attempting to replace an elements binding. Don't do that if no new elements are declared, but yield an error if attempting to do so. We could support this in the future (appending), but for now it's better to produce an error.

Fixes #9170

issue.title: bug: Assertion failure leading to crash in AOT and no `extern:ref.null` output in Interpreter.
issue.body:
### Summary

I have generated a test case that I executed with different runtimes. Compared to other runtimes, `WasmEdge`'s both interpreter and AOT modes produce inconsistent output.

### Current State

**Output from `WasmEdge` interpreter:**
```
-6.808752e106 (shortened for readability)
```

**Output from `WasmEdge` AOT:**
```
WasmEdge/lib/executor/executor.cpp:164: WasmEdge::Expect<std::vector<std::pair<WasmEdge::Variant<unsigned int, int, long unsigned int, long int, float, double, __int128 unsigned, __int128, __vector(2) long unsigned int, __vector(2) long int, __vector(4) unsigned int, __vector(4) int, __vector(8) short unsigned int, __vector(8) short int, __vector(16) unsigned char, __vector(16) signed char, __vector(4) float, __vector(2) double, WasmEdge::RefVariant>, WasmEdge::ValType> > > WasmEdge::Executor::Executor::invoke(const WasmEdge::Runtime::Instance::FunctionInstance*, WasmEdge::Span<const WasmEdge::Variant<unsigned int, int, long unsigned int, long int, float, double, __int128 unsigned, __int128, __vector(2) long unsigned int, __vector(2) long int, __vector(4) unsigned int, __vector(4) int, __vector(8) short unsigned int, __vector(8) short int, __vector(16) unsigned char, __vector(16) signed char, __vector(4) float, __vector(2) double, WasmEdge::RefVariant> >, WasmEdge::Span<const WasmEdge::ValType>): Assertion `Inst' failed.
Aborted
```

### Expected State

Based on other runtime outputs, the expected output is as follows:
```
extern:ref.null -6.808752e106
```

### Reproduction steps

**wasm file:** [wasm.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21822904/wasm.txt)
**wat file:** [wat.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21822907/wat.txt)

Steps to reproduce:

1. Rename `wasm.txt` to `test.wasm`
2. For interpreter, run: `wasmedge run --enable-all test.wasm to_test`
3. For AOT, run: `wasmedge compile test.wasm test.so`
    `wasmedge run --enable-all test.so to_test`

### Screenshots

![DESCRIPTION](LINK.png)


### Any logs you want to share for showing the specific issue

Here is the stack trace from the crash:
```
* thread #2, name = 'wasmedge', stop reason = signal SIGABRT

    frame #4: 0x00007ffff6c287f3 libc.so.6`__GI_abort at abort.c:79:7
    frame #5: 0x00007ffff6c2871b libc.so.6`__assert_fail_base.cold at assert.c:94:3
    frame #6: 0x00007ffff6c39e96 libc.so.6`__GI___assert_fail(assertion=<unavailable>, file=<unavailable>, line=<unavailable>, function=<unavailable>) at assert.c:103:3

commits.message:
feat: Comprehensive overhaul of UI, features, and bug fixes

This commit addresses a wide range of user feedback, including critical bug fixes, a full theme system implementation, and significant UI/UX enhancements, reflecting a proactive partnership approach.

- **Critical Bug Fixes:**
  - **Search Panel Crash:** Fixed a crash caused by undefined text in search results by adding a guard clause.
  - **Audio Player UI:** Corrected a visibility bug where controls were invisible on a white background by applying a theme-based accent color to the player.

- **Theme System Overhaul:**
  - **Dark Mode:** Re-introduced a full-featured Dark Mode for eye comfort.
  - **Default Theme:** Set the default theme to Sepia as requested.
  - **Consistent Theming:** Replaced all instances of hardcoded colors (e.g., #8b7355) with CSS variables (`var(--color-accent)`) across all components and styles. This ensures that changing the theme now applies consistently across the entire application.
  - **Refined Palettes:** Adjusted the color palettes for Sepia, Green, and Dark themes to be more aesthetically pleasing and have better contrast.

- **UI/UX Enhancements:**
  - **Verse Context Menu:** Implemented a new on-click context menu for each verse, providing options for Listen, Bookmark, Share, Tafsir, and Translation.
  - **Default Layout:** The default reading layout is now 'flow' mode (continuous text), with the option to toggle to 'list' mode.
  - **Font Size Control:** Re-implemented the font size control in the Settings page, which now correctly affects both list and flow layouts.
  - **Chapter Headers:** Redesigned the Surah headers to be more prominent and visually appealing.

- **Bug Fixes (from previous iterations):**
  - **Tafsir/Translation:** Ensured data fetching is correct by making settings apply instantly and providing a translation selector.
  - **Search Panel Data:** The backend now enriches search results with full verse details, fixing incorrect descriptions and navigation.

**Automated Reviews**: Continuous reviews of the pull requests including incremental commits.

**Codebase verification**:  Verifies the impact on the overall codebase and identifies missing changes.

**Insights into your code**:  Ask any questions on your codebase within the pull request 

**Chat about your code** : Chat with the bot around your code.The more you chat, the smarter it gets.

**Issue Validation**:  Validates the PR against the linked issues and identifies other related issues

issue.title: [Feedback] Network Console will be removed in Edge 143
issue.body:
Starting with Edge 143, the Network Console tool will be removed from Edge DevTools with no replacement. As our team shifts focus toward delivering more stable features and improving alignment with Chrome, we no longer have the capacity to maintain this tool. We recommend using the REST Client extension for VS Code for API development and testing.

If this feature is important to your workflow, we encourage you to share your feedback. Strong interest could help motivate bringing it to Chromium in the future.

comment.body:
When developers can't troubleshoot problems in Edge, we'll pull up a banner on the site to guide users to download Chrome, as we did before.

Maybe that's what Microsoft wants.

Safari has become the new era IE, and Edge wants to be the next Safari.
